1
00:00:00,288 --> 00:00:01,722
Previously on Alias...

2
00:00:01,723 --> 00:00:03,848
Sydney, this woman is an assassin.

3
00:00:03,849 --> 00:00:05,036
Vaughn trusted her.

4
00:00:05,222 --> 00:00:06,970
They worked together for seven years.

5
00:00:06,971 --> 00:00:10,233
- Sydney's contact is Renée Rienne.
- Really?

6
00:00:10,234 --> 00:00:11,638
Ms. Rienne has been helping Sydney

7
00:00:11,639 --> 00:00:13,950
with her investigation
of the Prophet Five conspiracy.

8
00:00:13,951 --> 00:00:17,438
Michael always told me
I could come to you.

9
00:00:18,952 --> 00:00:19,952
Yeah.

10
00:00:20,452 --> 00:00:24,727
These people killed my fiancé,
the father of my child.

11
00:00:25,078 --> 00:00:27,453
Our agreement is whatever I say it is.

12
00:00:27,766 --> 00:00:30,889
I'm the one who got you out of prison.
I can easily put you back.

13
00:00:30,890 --> 00:00:32,079
How's your daughter?

14
00:00:32,080 --> 00:00:34,205
Nadia has nothing to do with this.

15
00:00:34,639 --> 00:00:35,826
Oh, sure, she does.

16
00:01:23,005 --> 00:01:25,830
I'm at the archive. Your turn now.

17
00:02:04,686 --> 00:02:05,686
Got the key.

18
00:02:07,126 --> 00:02:09,813
It's transmitting now.
Insert key template.

19
00:02:12,411 --> 00:02:13,411
Perfect.

20
00:02:13,852 --> 00:02:15,414
I'm entering the archive.

21
00:02:25,852 --> 00:02:27,162
I need the lock number.

22
00:02:27,163 --> 00:02:28,536
So what are we looking for?

23
00:02:28,537 --> 00:02:31,035
All I know is it's intended
for Gordon Dean.

24
00:02:31,036 --> 00:02:33,750
The intel I received said
it will be left for him

25
00:02:33,751 --> 00:02:35,162
at the University of Rome

26
00:02:35,163 --> 00:02:38,162
inside a package shipped
to their museum archive.

27
00:02:38,163 --> 00:02:39,786
Well, how will we know which package?

28
00:02:39,787 --> 00:02:42,160
It will be sent from Milan,
from an alias...

29
00:02:42,161 --> 00:02:43,561
Marcello Demasi.

30
00:02:43,789 --> 00:02:47,601
I found the alias. Can you give me
a minute to find the name?

31
00:02:52,911 --> 00:02:54,785
Here it is. Marcello Demasi. Num...

32
00:02:54,786 --> 00:02:55,786
Sydney?

33
00:02:56,851 --> 00:02:57,851
Sydney Bristow?

34
00:02:58,975 --> 00:03:00,162
I don't believe it.

35
00:03:00,975 --> 00:03:01,975
Professor Choi.

36
00:03:02,600 --> 00:03:04,537
Sydney, I need the lock number.

37
00:03:05,348 --> 00:03:07,098
Look at you. You look great.

38
00:03:07,121 --> 00:03:08,225
Thank you.

39
00:03:08,226 --> 00:03:09,226
Sydney.

40
00:03:10,164 --> 00:03:11,475
What are you doing in Rome?

41
00:03:11,476 --> 00:03:14,974
Sabbatical. I'm teaching classes
and doing some research.

42
00:03:14,975 --> 00:03:16,162
And what about you?

43
00:03:16,599 --> 00:03:20,161
Oh, I've just been traveling...
12 countries in 22 months.

44
00:03:21,975 --> 00:03:22,975
Got it. 1222.

45
00:03:23,546 --> 00:03:27,039
I know that's a lot, but I won't have
much of a chance after the baby's born.

46
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:29,601
Now get out of there
before the Chancellor gets back.

47
00:03:29,602 --> 00:03:32,475
Well, I should let you get back
to your class.

48
00:03:32,476 --> 00:03:36,038
No problem. I'm on a lunch break.
We have plenty of time.

49
00:03:36,599 --> 00:03:37,599
Great.

50
00:03:49,600 --> 00:03:52,308
You know, uh,
I don't wanna be presumptive,

51
00:03:52,309 --> 00:03:53,662
but, uh, you married?

52
00:03:54,162 --> 00:03:55,162
Newlyweds.

53
00:03:55,788 --> 00:03:57,475
Ah, eager to start a family then?

54
00:03:57,476 --> 00:03:59,101
I guess you could say we dove right in.

55
00:03:59,102 --> 00:04:00,727
Well, he must be some guy.

56
00:04:00,977 --> 00:04:02,352
You seem really happy.

57
00:04:04,724 --> 00:04:05,724
He is.

58
00:04:10,603 --> 00:04:11,915
I found the shipment.

59
00:04:12,287 --> 00:04:13,974
I'm retrieving the package.

60
00:04:15,476 --> 00:04:16,476
I'll take that.

61
00:04:21,475 --> 00:04:22,912
Put it down. Step back.

62
00:04:55,352 --> 00:04:56,352
Got it.

63
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:00,038
I'm on my way to the extraction point.

64
00:05:00,039 --> 00:05:02,039
So is he here with you, your husband?

65
00:05:02,040 --> 00:05:03,165
He's at the hotel.

66
00:05:03,850 --> 00:05:06,975
I'd love for you to meet him.
We'll take you to dinner,

67
00:05:06,976 --> 00:05:08,728
if you'll just write down your number.

68
00:05:08,729 --> 00:05:11,479
Sure, I would like that.
Here, take my card.

69
00:05:23,778 --> 00:05:25,275
It was inside the sculpture.

70
00:05:25,276 --> 00:05:26,713
Any idea what it's for?

71
00:05:26,714 --> 00:05:27,714
No.

72
00:05:29,088 --> 00:05:32,038
So who was that man?

73
00:05:32,522 --> 00:05:33,584
- Choi?
- No one.

74
00:05:35,212 --> 00:05:36,774
He was from another life.

75
00:06:30,068 --> 00:06:31,628
She's still unresponsive.

76
00:06:31,629 --> 00:06:33,630
There's been no change since yesterday.

77
00:06:33,631 --> 00:06:35,818
I'm afraid the xylenol didn't work.

78
00:06:36,003 --> 00:06:38,649
The drug is still
in the experimental age.

79
00:06:38,650 --> 00:06:40,065
It deserves more time.

80
00:06:40,757 --> 00:06:42,484
Mr. Sloane, we've kept Nadia

81
00:06:42,485 --> 00:06:45,569
in a medically induced coma
for five months now.

82
00:06:46,877 --> 00:06:48,938
None of our procedures
have shown any promise.

83
00:06:48,939 --> 00:06:52,816
When we bring her out, she displays
the same violent propensities.

84
00:06:54,568 --> 00:06:56,692
Now these treatments
are extremely costly.

85
00:06:56,693 --> 00:06:58,593
Expense is not an issue.

86
00:06:58,691 --> 00:07:00,691
We've simply run out of options.

87
00:07:01,316 --> 00:07:04,252
At this point, anything that we may try
is unlikely to inspire change.

88
00:07:04,253 --> 00:07:06,440
It may even do more harm than good.

89
00:07:07,005 --> 00:07:08,817
I am not prepared to give up.

90
00:07:08,818 --> 00:07:09,818
Neither are we.

91
00:07:10,941 --> 00:07:14,689
In the meantime, I think
you should consider alternative care

92
00:07:14,690 --> 00:07:16,878
in a place a little more comfortable.

93
00:07:16,879 --> 00:07:18,379
Okay, thank you, Doctor.

94
00:07:28,664 --> 00:07:29,690
Yes?

95
00:07:29,691 --> 00:07:31,128
How is she doing today?

96
00:07:32,319 --> 00:07:33,319
I feel for you.

97
00:07:33,879 --> 00:07:36,466
I can't imagine how hard it must be

98
00:07:36,503 --> 00:07:38,940
looking into the face of your own sins.

99
00:07:39,066 --> 00:07:40,128
What do you want, Dean?

100
00:07:40,129 --> 00:07:43,691
Sydney Bristow has taken something
of mine... an access card.

101
00:07:43,692 --> 00:07:45,317
I want you to get it back.

102
00:07:45,380 --> 00:07:47,930
Why? What is it for?

103
00:07:48,132 --> 00:07:51,694
That's none of your concern.
48 hours. Don't let me down.

104
00:07:57,503 --> 00:07:59,193
Are you sure this is the right move?

105
00:07:59,194 --> 00:08:00,194
The right move?

106
00:08:00,195 --> 00:08:01,752
If they find out what you're up to...

107
00:08:01,753 --> 00:08:02,758
They won't.

108
00:08:02,759 --> 00:08:05,507
Besides, I don't think
I have the choice at this point.

109
00:08:05,508 --> 00:08:07,258
You're being paranoid again.

110
00:08:07,317 --> 00:08:10,692
You're too important to this operation
to be dismissed over a few setbacks.

111
00:08:10,693 --> 00:08:12,067
Well, maybe you're right,

112
00:08:12,068 --> 00:08:15,755
but some life insurance
will help me sleep better at night.

113
00:08:16,317 --> 00:08:17,567
You too, I imagine.

114
00:08:18,444 --> 00:08:20,317
Odds are if they terminate me,

115
00:08:20,318 --> 00:08:23,443
they'll decide our entire cell
is a security risk.

116
00:08:24,506 --> 00:08:27,131
I'll let you know
when Sloane contacts me.

117
00:08:45,694 --> 00:08:46,694
Hello, Jack.

118
00:08:46,819 --> 00:08:49,754
Arvin, good news.
Sydney's mission in Italy was a success.

119
00:08:49,755 --> 00:08:51,317
Yes, I already knew that.

120
00:08:52,379 --> 00:08:53,379
Did you?

121
00:08:54,945 --> 00:08:55,945
How?

122
00:08:58,004 --> 00:08:59,254
Gordon Dean told me.

123
00:09:00,355 --> 00:09:08,355
Translation : Anyone Sixe Guilamu
Transcript : Raceman
Synchro : Guilamu
Suggestions critics insults : aliassub@gmail.com
www.forom.com

124
00:09:38,907 --> 00:09:41,406
Marshall ran analysis
on the card you retrieved?

125
00:09:41,407 --> 00:09:44,346
He suspects it's an access key
for a secure network.

126
00:09:44,347 --> 00:09:47,097
So we just have to figure out
which network.

127
00:09:47,533 --> 00:09:50,719
Luckily, there are only
10 billion secure networks in the world.

128
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:53,967
We may have a dead end on that side,
but we intercepted Dean's property.

129
00:09:53,968 --> 00:09:57,030
I'm guessing
he's not too happy about that, so...

130
00:09:57,096 --> 00:09:58,658
I'll take what I can get.

131
00:10:02,532 --> 00:10:05,594
- Delivery for Sydney Bristow.
- Hey, come on in.

132
00:10:06,532 --> 00:10:08,780
Just put it in the nursery.
It's right through there.

133
00:10:08,781 --> 00:10:09,781
Thanks.

134
00:10:14,847 --> 00:10:15,847
Crib.

135
00:10:21,532 --> 00:10:24,969
You know, the, uh,
the nursery could use a little work.

136
00:10:25,658 --> 00:10:28,158
I don't know. I think it's kind of airy.

137
00:10:29,781 --> 00:10:31,971
I'll grab my bag.
We can head in to work.

138
00:10:31,972 --> 00:10:33,655
I thought you were taking the day off.

139
00:10:33,656 --> 00:10:34,656
I was.

140
00:10:35,097 --> 00:10:38,972
That was before we had ten billion
secure networks to analyze.

141
00:10:40,908 --> 00:10:42,220
I have a better idea.

142
00:10:42,348 --> 00:10:43,907
First, let's set up the crib, and then

143
00:10:43,908 --> 00:10:44,966
at least that way,

144
00:10:44,967 --> 00:10:46,968
we'll know we got something
accomplished today.

145
00:10:46,969 --> 00:10:48,719
It's okay. I'll do it later.

146
00:10:48,909 --> 00:10:50,971
What could it take, half an hour?

147
00:10:53,283 --> 00:10:55,597
I used to think that stuff
would be so fun...

148
00:10:55,598 --> 00:10:59,560
decorating a room
and picking out colors.

149
00:11:03,473 --> 00:11:06,973
It hasn't turned out exactly the way
I thought it would.

150
00:11:12,285 --> 00:11:13,285
Yeah?

151
00:11:14,034 --> 00:11:16,159
I was first contacted a month ago.

152
00:11:16,598 --> 00:11:18,910
It was during my sentencing hearings.

153
00:11:19,035 --> 00:11:21,847
As I told your father,
the terms were simple.

154
00:11:22,723 --> 00:11:23,953
They offered to sway

155
00:11:23,954 --> 00:11:26,660
the committee's decision
for my release...

156
00:11:28,160 --> 00:11:30,785
and I, in turn,
would be indebted to them.

157
00:11:32,348 --> 00:11:35,179
It was not made clear
what that would entail,

158
00:11:35,180 --> 00:11:36,348
but I had an idea.

159
00:11:36,971 --> 00:11:39,347
You've been lying to us this whole time.

160
00:11:39,348 --> 00:11:40,910
There's no justification.

161
00:11:42,283 --> 00:11:44,783
However, faced with spending
the rest of my life in prison

162
00:11:44,784 --> 00:11:46,649
while my daughter
was in the hospital, I...

163
00:11:46,650 --> 00:11:48,642
Nadia hasn't made any improvement.

164
00:11:48,643 --> 00:11:51,161
Why admit this to us now?
What's changed?

165
00:11:51,660 --> 00:11:53,910
Nadia won't be getting better, Jack.

166
00:11:57,409 --> 00:12:00,346
If I have to face a life
without my daughter...

167
00:12:01,661 --> 00:12:03,723
I still have to live with myself.

168
00:12:06,535 --> 00:12:10,347
It sounds hollow, I know,
in light of what I just told you...

169
00:12:11,035 --> 00:12:13,535
but I consider you both to be my family.

170
00:12:14,724 --> 00:12:16,786
You expect us to forgive you now?

171
00:12:17,098 --> 00:12:18,535
No, Sydney, not at all.

172
00:12:19,909 --> 00:12:22,372
I know how much pain
Dean has caused you

173
00:12:22,373 --> 00:12:24,034
as well as Rachel Gibson.

174
00:12:24,521 --> 00:12:27,183
I have damaged your investigation
enough.

175
00:12:28,971 --> 00:12:32,658
Ironically, Dean's arrangement
puts me in a unique position.

176
00:12:32,659 --> 00:12:36,096
The last thing he expects of me
is to double cross him.

177
00:12:36,285 --> 00:12:37,720
You'll help us arrest him?

178
00:12:37,721 --> 00:12:38,721
Yes.

179
00:12:39,110 --> 00:12:40,800
He's tasked me
with recovering something

180
00:12:40,801 --> 00:12:42,301
you took from him... an access card.

181
00:12:42,302 --> 00:12:43,536
I can use that as bait.

182
00:12:43,786 --> 00:12:45,847
Understand something.
If this is a setup...

183
00:12:45,848 --> 00:12:47,785
It's not, Sydney, I assure you.

184
00:12:49,411 --> 00:12:51,222
Once we have Dean in custody,

185
00:12:51,223 --> 00:12:53,722
he will be forced
to expose his organization,

186
00:12:53,723 --> 00:12:57,035
and you will have all the answers
you're looking for.

187
00:13:04,161 --> 00:13:06,098
You have a way to contact Dean?

188
00:13:09,724 --> 00:13:10,724
Hello?

189
00:13:11,095 --> 00:13:12,095
It's me.

190
00:13:13,098 --> 00:13:14,535
I have what you wanted.

191
00:13:15,287 --> 00:13:17,412
Good. I knew I could count on you.

192
00:13:20,285 --> 00:13:21,597
Where should we meet?

193
00:13:21,662 --> 00:13:23,349
Get a pen. Write this down.

194
00:13:25,224 --> 00:13:27,286
The meeting place is a racetrack.

195
00:13:27,348 --> 00:13:30,660
Dean may trust Sloane,
but he's still being cautious.

196
00:13:30,785 --> 00:13:33,222
He picked this location
because it's safe...

197
00:13:33,223 --> 00:13:35,785
several exit strategies,
a large crowd to blend in with.

198
00:13:35,786 --> 00:13:38,661
That or maybe he's got
Lollipop in the second.

199
00:13:38,774 --> 00:13:41,284
We'll have to grab him
before he has the chance to slip out.

200
00:13:41,285 --> 00:13:42,472
That won't be easy.

201
00:13:42,662 --> 00:13:44,908
Dean doesn't go anywhere
without a security detail.

202
00:13:44,909 --> 00:13:48,411
It'll most likely be two men
heavily armed, nearly invisible.

203
00:13:48,412 --> 00:13:50,909
We can assume that one
will shadow Dean, the other Sloane.

204
00:13:50,910 --> 00:13:53,597
Um, sorry. Is anybody else
having déja vu here?

205
00:13:53,598 --> 00:13:56,597
I mean, first Sloane was good,
then he's bad, now he's good again?

206
00:13:56,598 --> 00:13:59,473
Although I guess he was bad at first,
I just thought...

207
00:13:59,474 --> 00:14:02,224
We have a significant
tactical disadvantage.

208
00:14:02,225 --> 00:14:04,850
Dean knows what we look like.
He can I.D. every one of us.

209
00:14:04,851 --> 00:14:07,038
Not everyone. He's never seen me...

210
00:14:07,451 --> 00:14:09,411
but I look forward
to making his acquaintance.

211
00:14:09,412 --> 00:14:11,162
Good. Tom, you'll take lead.

212
00:14:11,534 --> 00:14:13,992
Dixon, Sydney, Rachel,
you'll provide support in the field.

213
00:14:13,993 --> 00:14:17,159
I want a plan drafted within the hour.
Wheels up at 1500.

214
00:14:17,212 --> 00:14:20,287
We may not have another chance
like this. Let's make it count.

215
00:14:37,405 --> 00:14:39,319
Dean's reserved you a seat
in the grandstand.

216
00:14:39,320 --> 00:14:41,400
He won't arrive
until he's confirmed you're alone.

217
00:14:41,401 --> 00:14:42,833
If we put a transmitter on you,

218
00:14:42,834 --> 00:14:44,647
his security countermeasures
may detect it,

219
00:14:44,648 --> 00:14:46,710
so I'll be tracking you remotely.

220
00:14:47,022 --> 00:14:48,084
You'll need this.

221
00:14:48,274 --> 00:14:49,898
It's a facsimile, I assume.

222
00:14:49,899 --> 00:14:51,086
No, it's the real card.

223
00:14:51,087 --> 00:14:53,149
Dean may verify it with a reader.

224
00:14:53,774 --> 00:14:55,930
We'll move in as soon as
we've intercepted his men,

225
00:14:55,931 --> 00:14:57,803
but until then, you'll have to stall.

226
00:14:57,804 --> 00:14:58,804
Okay.

227
00:15:01,616 --> 00:15:04,427
I hacked into the closed-circuit feeds.
We're ready to go.

228
00:15:04,428 --> 00:15:05,428
Okay, you're up.

229
00:15:06,364 --> 00:15:07,364
Look, Sydney...

230
00:15:08,553 --> 00:15:11,865
I may have lost the opportunity
to save my own child.

231
00:15:12,304 --> 00:15:14,428
I only hope that by taking out Dean,

232
00:15:14,429 --> 00:15:16,491
I will have helped to save yours.

233
00:15:17,424 --> 00:15:18,424
Good luck.

234
00:15:25,610 --> 00:15:27,860
Okay. Dixon and Tom are in position.

235
00:15:28,859 --> 00:15:30,109
No sign of Dean yet.

236
00:15:30,299 --> 00:15:33,361
He won't reveal himself
until Sloane is in place.

237
00:15:39,736 --> 00:15:41,360
Excuse me. Mama comin' through!

238
00:15:41,361 --> 00:15:43,611
Watch out. Don't jostle the package!

239
00:15:48,673 --> 00:15:49,673
How y'all doin'?

240
00:15:50,050 --> 00:15:51,050
How y'all doin'?

241
00:15:51,672 --> 00:15:53,858
You gonna help me
pick a winner today, skinny?

242
00:15:53,859 --> 00:15:55,646
Ha ha. He's cute...

243
00:15:55,798 --> 00:15:57,498
for a Sheik.

244
00:16:17,250 --> 00:16:18,918
Excuse me that's my seat.

245
00:16:18,919 --> 00:16:22,562
Okay, laser mic's on target, Phoenix.
Reception's good.

246
00:16:28,313 --> 00:16:30,063
Hey, Base. You got a visual?

247
00:16:30,687 --> 00:16:32,187
Affirmative, Sidewinder.

248
00:16:33,063 --> 00:16:37,188
Good, 'cause, uh, I was wondering,
what do you think of this suit?

249
00:16:37,653 --> 00:16:38,683
Pretty sweet, huh?

250
00:16:38,684 --> 00:16:40,312
Yeah, it's a nice suit on you.

251
00:16:40,313 --> 00:16:44,000
Blue's a good color.
And for you as well, Director Bristow.

252
00:16:44,122 --> 00:16:47,559
Thanks. Oracle, can you get us
a closer look at Sloane?

253
00:16:50,500 --> 00:16:51,812
- How's that?
- Fine.

254
00:16:54,435 --> 00:16:55,435
I got him.

